/* cloud+ :: content/domain6.js — lazy-loaded reading module for CV0-004 Domain 6 (Troubleshooting, deep). */
window.CLOUDPLUS = window.CLOUDPLUS || {}; CLOUDPLUS.reading = CLOUDPLUS.reading || {};
CLOUDPLUS.reading[6] = [];
CLOUDPLUS.reading[6].push(
  {heading:"The Structured Troubleshooting Methodology in the Cloud", body:"<p>Every Domain 6 question rests on a single discipline: a repeatable, ordered method for moving from a vague symptom to a verified fix. CompTIA frames it as a seven-step loop, and the reason it is tested so heavily is that undisciplined engineers skip steps under pressure - they change a firewall rule before they have a theory, or close a ticket before they have verified the fix. In a shared, multi-tenant cloud where a single change can ripple across regions and tenants, that discipline matters even more than it did on-premises, because the blast radius of a wrong change is no longer one server in one rack but potentially an entire service consumed by thousands of users.</p><h3>The seven steps</h3><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Identify the problem</span> - gather symptoms, question the user, reproduce if possible, and define the scope (one user, one region, one service, or global).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Establish a theory of probable cause</span> - form a hypothesis, starting with the simplest and most likely explanation (the obvious before the obscure).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Test the theory</span> - prove or disprove the hypothesis with a targeted test; if it fails, form a new theory or escalate.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Establish a plan of action</span> - decide the fix and identify side effects, rollback paths, and the maintenance window.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Implement the solution</span> - apply the change, ideally through infrastructure-as-code so it is auditable and repeatable.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Verify full system functionality</span> - confirm the symptom is gone and nothing else broke, and implement preventive measures.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Document findings</span> - record the cause, the fix, and the lessons in the ticket and the runbook.</li></ul><h3>Why scope comes first</h3><p>The single most valuable output of step one is <em>scope</em>. Before theorizing, you must know whether the issue affects one user or every user, one availability zone or the whole region, one microservice or the entire mesh. Scope is what separates a five-minute fix from a multi-team incident bridge. A symptom reported as the whole site is down frequently turns out to be one browser, one VPN, or one office's egress path, and a symptom reported as a minor glitch sometimes turns out to be a regional control-plane degradation. A quick provider status check often resolves scope instantly - if <code>aws health describe-events</code> or the Azure Service Health blade shows a regional outage, your theory work is over and the action becomes communication and failover, not configuration changes.</p><pre><code>$ aws health describe-events --filter eventStatusCodes=open \\\n    --query 'events[].[service,region,statusCode,eventTypeCode]' --output text\nRDS   us-east-1   open   AWS_RDS_OPERATIONAL_ISSUE\n$ curl -s -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}\\n' https://status.example-cloud.com/api/v2/status.json\n200</code></pre><p>If the health API names a service you depend on, you have your scope without forming a single theory about your own configuration.</p><h3>Corporate change and policy impact</h3><p>In an enterprise, the troubleshooting loop runs inside a governance frame. Almost every fix in a production cloud is itself a <span class='keyterm'>change</span> that must pass through change management. A standard change (a pre-approved, low-risk fix) may proceed immediately, but a normal change requires a change request, peer review, and an approved maintenance window. The exam stresses that even a correct technical fix can be the wrong action if it violates policy - pushing an emergency firewall change without a change record can breach compliance frameworks (PCI DSS, SOC 2) that demand an audit trail. Conversely, an <span class='keyterm'>emergency change</span> process exists precisely so that a genuine outage can be remediated fast and documented retroactively. The mature engineer knows which lane a given fix belongs in: a routine config tweak goes through normal change, while a production-down incident invokes the emergency path, with the after-action documentation completed once service is restored.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Change type</th><th>Risk / timing</th><th>Approval path</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Standard</td><td>Low risk, pre-approved</td><td>No CAB review; proceed</td></tr><tr><td>Normal</td><td>Planned, moderate risk</td><td>Change request + CAB/peer review + window</td></tr><tr><td>Emergency</td><td>Production down, urgent</td><td>Expedited approval; document after the fact</td></tr></tbody></table><blockquote>Identify, theorize, test, plan, implement, verify, document - and never let a fix outrun the change record that authorizes it.</blockquote><h3>Bottom-up, top-down, and divide-and-conquer</h3><p>Within the loop, the OSI-style strategies still apply. <strong>Bottom-up</strong> starts at the physical and network layers (is the instance reachable at all?) and works upward toward the application. <strong>Top-down</strong> starts at the user-facing symptom (the web page returns a 502) and drills down. <strong>Divide-and-conquer</strong> jumps to a middle layer - often DNS or the load balancer - and decides which half of the stack to investigate next. Cloud architectures reward divide-and-conquer because the load balancer and DNS sit at natural chokepoints where you can quickly tell whether the problem is in front of the application or behind it. A single <code>curl -v</code> against the public endpoint, then against the backend directly, often halves the search space in one move.</p><h3>Documenting for the next responder</h3><p>The final step is the one engineers most often skip, and the exam knows it. Documentation is not bureaucratic overhead - it is what turns a painful three-hour incident into a five-minute fix the next time the same symptom appears. Good documentation captures the observed symptom, the scope, the disproved theories (so the next person does not repeat them), the root cause, the exact change applied, and the preventive measure added. In a cloud team, that record lives in the ticket, the runbook, and ideally as a codified guardrail (a new alarm, a policy, or an IaC change) so the class of failure cannot recur silently.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>When a question asks for the <em>next</em> step, find where the scenario sits in the seven-step loop and pick the step that immediately follows. If a tech has just applied a fix, the next step is <strong>verify</strong>, not document. If a theory was just disproved, the next step is to form a <em>new</em> theory or escalate - not to implement anything. Watch for answers that skip steps; the methodical choice is almost always correct.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>Users report a SaaS app is slow only from the Frankfurt office. A junior engineer wants to resize the database immediately. The correct first move is to identify and scope: is it one office (network path) or all users (the service)? Scoping reveals a regional peering issue, and resizing the database would have been wasted change risk - and an unapproved one at that.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[6].push(
  {heading:"Deployment Issues: Incompatibility and Misconfiguration", body:"<p>Most failed cloud deployments do not fail because the cloud is down - they fail because something the team supplied is wrong: an incompatible component, a misconfigured resource, a stale definition, or a quota that was hit. Objective 6.1 is essentially a catalog of self-inflicted deployment failures, and the troubleshooting skill is matching a symptom to the right category quickly. Because these failures surface at deploy time rather than under production load, they are usually cheap to fix once correctly classified - and expensive when misclassified, because the engineer ends up tuning the wrong dimension entirely.</p><h3>Incompatibility</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Incompatibility</span> appears when two components that must work together do not agree on a version, format, or interface. A container image built for <code>linux/amd64</code> refuses to schedule on Graviton (<code>arm64</code>) nodes; a Terraform module pinned to an old provider version errors against a new API; an application compiled against one runtime crashes on a newer one. The tell is an error that surfaces immediately at deploy or first run, not under load. The fix is usually pinning or rebuilding to a compatible version, and the lesson is to declare version constraints explicitly rather than relying on <code>latest</code>. You can confirm an architecture mismatch directly from the image manifest:</p><pre><code>$ docker manifest inspect myapp:1.4 | grep architecture\n          \"architecture\": \"amd64\",\n$ kubectl describe pod web-xyz | grep -i exec\n  Warning  Failed  exec format error   # amd64 image on an arm64 node</code></pre><p>An <code>exec format error</code> is the unmistakable signature of a CPU-architecture incompatibility; the fix is a multi-arch image build, not more memory or more replicas.</p><h3>Misconfiguration: the four sub-types</h3><p>CompTIA breaks deployment misconfiguration into four named problems the exam expects you to distinguish:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Misconfiguration</th><th>Symptom</th><th>Typical fix</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Resource allocation</td><td>Pods stuck Pending; instance fails to launch (InsufficientInstanceCapacity)</td><td>Right-size requests/limits; choose available instance family or AZ</td></tr><tr><td>Permission issues</td><td>AccessDenied / 403 on an API call the app must make</td><td>Correct the IAM role, policy, or service-account binding</td></tr><tr><td>Oversubscription</td><td>Noisy-neighbor latency; CPU steal time; throttled vCPUs</td><td>Move to dedicated/reserved capacity; reduce contention ratio</td></tr><tr><td>Sizing issues</td><td>OOMKilled containers; disk full; instance too small or too large</td><td>Resize compute/memory/storage to the real workload profile</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Permission issues in practice</h3><p>Permission failures are the most common cloud deployment defect because identity is the new control plane. A deployment that worked in staging fails in production simply because the production service account lacks one IAM permission. The diagnosis is almost always in the error body - a clear <code>AccessDenied</code> naming the action and resource. A quick check confirms the identity actually in use:</p><pre><code>$ aws sts get-caller-identity\n{\n    \"UserId\": \"AROAEXAMPLE:deploy-session\",\n    \"Account\": \"123456789012\",\n    \"Arn\": \"arn:aws:sts::123456789012:assumed-role/deploy-role/deploy-session\"\n}</code></pre><p>If the ARN is not the role you expected, the credential chain (environment variables, instance profile, assumed role) picked up the wrong identity - a misconfiguration, not a code bug. The discipline here is to read the error string literally: it names both the action that was denied and the resource it targeted, which is usually enough to write the exact policy statement that closes the gap.</p><h3>Oversubscription versus sizing</h3><p>Students conflate <span class='keyterm'>oversubscription</span> with a simple <span class='keyterm'>sizing issue</span>, but they are different. Sizing means the resource you reserved is genuinely too small for the workload (a 512 MB container that needs 1 GB and gets OOMKilled). Oversubscription means the provider has sold more virtual capacity than the physical host has, so your correctly sized VM still suffers because neighbors are contending for the same cores - visible as elevated <code>%steal</code> in <code>top</code> or <code>vmstat</code>. The fix for sizing is to grow the resource; the fix for oversubscription is to reduce contention by moving to dedicated tenancy or a less crowded instance class.</p><pre><code>$ vmstat 1 3\nprocs ----cpu----\n r b   us sy id wa st\n 2 0   30  5 25  0 40   # st (steal) = 40% -> host is oversubscribed\n$ free -m | grep Mem\nMem:  490  470  20      # almost no free memory -> sizing problem, not steal</code></pre><p>High steal time points at oversubscription; near-zero free memory with OOMKills points at sizing. Reading the right counter prevents the classic mistake of buying a bigger instance to cure a noisy-neighbor problem that a dedicated host would fix for free. The two can also coexist and feed each other: an undersized instance that is also on a busy host suffers twice, and the engineer who fixes only one dimension is puzzled that performance barely improved. The disciplined approach is to measure both before changing anything, decide which is dominant, and change one variable at a time so the effect of each fix is observable rather than guessed.</p><h3>Resource allocation failures</h3><p>Allocation problems show up at schedule time. In Kubernetes a pod that cannot be placed stays <code>Pending</code>, and the reason is in the events:</p><pre><code>$ kubectl describe pod web-7d9c -n prod\nEvents:\n  Warning  FailedScheduling  default-scheduler\n    0/6 nodes are available: 6 Insufficient memory.</code></pre><p>That message says the requests exceed available node capacity - either the requests are too high (sizing) or the cluster needs more nodes (allocation). Reading the event text, rather than guessing, is what separates a quick fix from an afternoon of churn. At the IaaS layer the equivalent is an <code>InsufficientInstanceCapacity</code> error, where the provider simply has no spare hardware of that type in that AZ at that moment - the remedy is to try another AZ, another instance family, or a capacity reservation.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Map the symptom to the sub-type: a 403/AccessDenied is a <strong>permission</strong> issue; OOMKilled or disk-full is a <strong>sizing</strong> issue; CPU steal and noisy neighbors point to <strong>oversubscription</strong>; a pod that cannot be scheduled is a <strong>resource allocation</strong> issue. The exam loves to give you the exact error string - read it literally, because the verb and the resource name usually name the category for you.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[6].push(
  {heading:"Deployment Issues: Outdated Definitions, Deprecation, and Outages", body:"<p>Beyond fresh misconfiguration, deployments break because something that used to work has rotted or been retired. This section covers outdated component definitions, deprecation of functionality, and provider outages - failures where the code did not change but the world around it did. These are insidious precisely because nothing in your repository changed; the failure appears to come from nowhere, and the engineer who assumes their own code is the cause wastes hours.</p><h3>Outdated component definitions</h3><p>An <span class='keyterm'>outdated component definition</span> is a stale template, image, or manifest that no longer matches reality. A launch template that references an AMI ID that has been deregistered, a Helm chart pinned to an image tag that was deleted from the registry, or an IaC module that still names a discontinued instance type will all fail at deploy time. The signature is a deployment that succeeded last month and fails today with no code change. The fix is to refresh the definition - update the AMI/image reference, regenerate the lockfile, and ideally automate image rebuilds so definitions never drift far from current.</p><pre><code>$ aws ec2 describe-images --image-ids ami-0deadbeef0\nAn error occurred (InvalidAMIID.NotFound): The image id does not exist   # deregistered AMI\n$ docker pull registry.example.com/web:1.2.0\nmanifest unknown: manifest tagged by 1.2.0 is not found   # deleted image tag</code></pre><p>Both errors say the definition points at something that no longer exists. The remediation is to repoint at a current artifact and, more importantly, to stop hard-coding mutable references that can vanish underneath you. The deeper prevention is to treat artifacts as immutable and version-pinned but kept current by automation: a scheduled rebuild that bakes a fresh, patched base image and updates the reference through a reviewed pull request keeps definitions from drifting into staleness without a human ever having to remember to do it.</p><h3>Deprecation of functionality</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Deprecation</span> is the provider's planned, announced retirement of a feature, API version, or runtime. Unlike an outage, deprecation is scheduled and communicated months ahead - a Lambda runtime reaches end of support, a TLS version is disabled, or a v1 API endpoint is removed in favor of v2. The danger is ignoring the notices. An application calling a deprecated API begins returning errors on the cutoff date even though nothing in the app changed. A verbose request makes the warning visible while there is still time:</p><pre><code>$ curl -v https://api.example-cloud.com/v1/instances\n&lt; HTTP/2 200\n&lt; warning: 299 - \"Deprecated API: v1 retires 2026-09-01, migrate to /v2\"\n&lt; sunset: Tue, 01 Sep 2026 00:00:00 GMT</code></pre><p>The <code>Sunset</code> header and a <code>299</code> warning are formal deprecation signals; treating them as noise is how a quiet warning becomes a production outage on the cutoff date. The fix is proactive migration during the announced window, not reactive firefighting after the endpoint returns a hard 410 Gone. The same discipline applies to runtimes and managed-service versions: a database engine version or a serverless runtime nearing end of support should be tracked as a deprecation deadline with an owner and a date, because the provider will eventually force the upgrade on its own schedule, often during a maintenance window you did not choose, if you have not moved first.</p><h3>Outages: full versus partial</h3><p>An <span class='keyterm'>outage</span> is a provider-side failure, and the exam distinguishes full from partial. A <strong>full outage</strong> takes an entire service or region offline - nothing in that scope works. A <strong>partial outage</strong> degrades a subset: one availability zone, one feature of a service (object reads work but writes fail), or elevated error rates rather than total failure. Distinguishing them changes your response:</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Full outage</th><th>Partial / degraded</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Scope</td><td>Whole service or region down</td><td>One AZ, one feature, or elevated errors</td></tr><tr><td>Detection</td><td>All requests fail; status page red</td><td>Intermittent 5xx; status page yellow</td></tr><tr><td>Right response</td><td>Fail over to another region/provider</td><td>Retry with backoff; shift load off the bad AZ</td></tr><tr><td>Your fix?</td><td>No - provider must restore</td><td>Mitigate at your layer while provider recovers</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Confirming it is the provider, not you</h3><p>Before declaring an outage, confirm scope independently rather than trusting one failing request. The provider health API is authoritative, and an independent probe from outside your own VPC rules out a local network fault:</p><pre><code>$ aws health describe-events --filter eventStatusCodes=open \\\n    --query 'events[].[service,region,statusCode]' --output text\nEC2   us-east-1   open\n$ curl -s -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}\\n' https://status.example-cloud.com/api/v2/status\n200\n$ dig +short api.example-cloud.com @1.1.1.1\n203.0.113.42   # name still resolves -> not a DNS-layer outage</code></pre><p>If your own resources fail but the health API and an independent <code>curl</code> from outside your VPC both succeed, the fault is more likely in your configuration than in the cloud. The discipline of confirming scope prevents the classic mistake of opening a high-severity provider ticket for what is actually a local security-group typo. Conversely, when the health API confirms the incident, the correct action is to invoke your failover runbook and communicate status, not to keep editing your own resources hoping to route around a problem you do not own.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>NOTE</div><p>Architect for outages before they happen: multi-AZ by default, multi-region for tier-1 workloads, and retries with exponential backoff and jitter so a partial outage degrades gracefully instead of cascading. Troubleshooting an outage you designed for is mostly confirming that failover triggered correctly - which is a far calmer place to be than discovering you had a single point of failure during the incident itself.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>If the scenario says the provider status page shows an incident, the answer is rarely to reconfigure your resources - it is to invoke failover or wait and communicate. Reserve configuration fixes for symptoms that your own status checks show are local. A <em>deprecation</em> is announced in advance; an <em>outage</em> is unplanned - do not confuse the two.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[6].push(
  {heading:"Deployment Issues: Resource Limits and Regional Availability", body:"<p>The final pieces of objective 6.1 are the limits the platform itself imposes - API throttling and service quotas - and the fact that not every service exists in every region. These failures are subtle because the request is well-formed and the credentials are valid; the platform simply says no. The trap on the exam is that all three can look like a generic deployment failure, yet each demands a completely different response, and retrying blindly helps only one of them.</p><h3>API throttling</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>API throttling</span> (rate limiting) protects shared services by capping how many calls a client may make per unit time. When you exceed the rate, the API returns a specific status and a hint about when to retry. In HTTP terms this is a <code>429 Too Many Requests</code>; AWS surfaces it as <code>ThrottlingException</code> or <code>RequestLimitExceeded</code>. The signature is failures that appear only under high call volume - a deploy loop that creates hundreds of resources, or a poorly written client that polls a status endpoint in a tight loop.</p><pre><code>$ for i in $(seq 1 50); do\n    curl -s -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code} ' https://api.example-cloud.com/v2/health\n  done\n200 200 200 200 429 429 200 429 429 429 ...\n$ curl -sD - -o /dev/null https://api.example-cloud.com/v2/health | grep -i retry-after\nretry-after: 2</code></pre><p>The <code>Retry-After</code> header tells you exactly how long to wait. The fix is almost never to ask for the limit to be raised first - it is to implement <strong>exponential backoff with jitter</strong> and respect that header. Retrying immediately makes throttling worse by adding to the very storm that triggered it, and a thundering herd of synchronized retries can keep an otherwise-recovered service pinned down.</p><h3>Service quotas (limits)</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Service quotas</span> are hard or soft ceilings on how much of a resource an account may hold - number of VPCs, Elastic IPs, vCPUs per region, or function concurrency. Quotas differ from throttling: throttling limits the <em>rate</em> of calls; a quota limits the <em>total</em> count of resources. A quota failure stops a deploy cold with a message like <code>LimitExceeded: You have requested more vCPUs than your current limit of 64</code>. The diagnosis is to read your current usage against the quota:</p><pre><code>$ aws service-quotas get-service-quota \\\n    --service-code ec2 --quota-code L-1216C47A \\\n    --query 'Quota.[QuotaName,Value]' --output text\nRunning On-Demand Standard instances    64.0\n$ aws ec2 describe-instances --filters Name=instance-state-name,Values=running \\\n    --query 'length(Reservations[].Instances[])'\n64   # usage equals the quota -> request an increase, do not retry</code></pre><p>If usage equals the quota, the fix is a quota-increase request (often human-reviewed and not instant) or reducing consumption - not retrying. Treating a quota error like a transient failure and retrying is a classic wasted-effort trap, because the ceiling is fixed until a human or an automated approval raises it.</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>API throttling</th><th>Service quota</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Limits</td><td>Calls per second/minute</td><td>Total resources or capacity</td></tr><tr><td>Status / error</td><td>429 / ThrottlingException</td><td>LimitExceeded / quota exceeded</td></tr><tr><td>Right response</td><td>Backoff and retry; slow the client</td><td>Request increase or free resources</td></tr><tr><td>Retry helps?</td><td>Yes, after a delay</td><td>No - the ceiling is fixed until raised</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Regional service availability</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Regional service availability</span> failures happen when an application assumes a service or feature exists everywhere, but the provider has not launched it in the target region. A newer managed-AI service or a specific instance generation may be in us-east-1 but absent in a smaller region, so the deploy errors with something like <code>UnsupportedOperation</code> or <code>service is not available in this region</code>. This is not a quota or a permission problem - the resource type simply does not exist there. A quick capability check before deploying avoids the surprise:</p><pre><code>$ aws ec2 describe-instance-type-offerings --region eu-south-2 \\\n    --filters Name=instance-type,Values=p5.48xlarge \\\n    --query 'InstanceTypeOfferings[].InstanceType' --output text\n$   # empty result = that instance type is not offered in eu-south-2\n$ aws ec2 describe-regions --query 'Regions[].RegionName' --output text\nus-east-1 us-west-2 eu-west-1 eu-south-2 ap-southeast-1</code></pre><p>An empty result confirms the type is unavailable in that region, pointing you to a different region or a substitute resource rather than a configuration tweak. The broader lesson is that region parity is never guaranteed: new services and instance families roll out region by region, and a deployment that is portable in theory can still fail in practice because a dependency has not landed in the target region yet. The same caveat applies to compliance boundaries: a workload that must stay within a data-sovereignty region cannot simply fall back to wherever a service happens to exist, so the architect has to confirm capability and jurisdiction together before committing to a region.</p><h3>Soft limits, hard limits, and lead time</h3><p>A practical subtlety the exam expects you to appreciate is the difference between a <em>soft</em> limit and a <em>hard</em> limit. Soft limits are default quotas the provider will raise on request, often within minutes for small increases and within a day or two for large ones; hard limits are architectural ceilings that cannot be raised at all, forcing you to redesign (for example, sharding across multiple accounts to escape a per-account maximum). Because even a soft-limit increase has lead time, capacity planning is part of troubleshooting prevention: discovering a quota wall in the middle of a Black Friday scale-up is far more painful than requesting the headroom a week earlier. When a deploy fails on a quota, the immediate triage is to check whether the limit is adjustable and, if so, to file the increase while pursuing any short-term reduction in consumption.</p><h3>Distinguishing the three at a glance</h3><p>The fastest mental model is to ask what the platform is actually objecting to. If it objects to <em>how fast</em> you are asking, it is throttling - slow down. If it objects to <em>how much</em> you already have, it is a quota - request more or free some. If it objects to <em>what</em> you are asking for in <em>where</em> you are asking, it is regional availability - move or substitute. Each error string carries the verb that tells you which one, and reading it literally is faster than any trial and error.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A Terraform apply that works in us-east-1 fails in a new EU region with <code>UnsupportedOperation</code> for a GPU instance type. The team wastes an hour checking IAM and quotas. The real cause is regional availability: that GPU family has not launched in the EU region, so the fix is to select an available type or region, not to edit policies.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Distinguish the three platform-says-no failures: <strong>429/throttling</strong> means slow down and back off; <strong>quota/LimitExceeded</strong> means request an increase or free resources (retrying will not help); <strong>regional availability</strong> means the service or type is not offered there at all. The error string usually names which one it is.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[6].push(
  {heading:"Network Issues: Core Network Services (DHCP, DNS, NTP, NAT)", body:"<p>Objective 6.2 begins with the infrastructure services that everything else depends on. When DHCP, DNS, NTP, or NAT misbehaves, the symptom often looks like an application bug, which is why network-service triage is the most valuable troubleshooting skill in the domain. The principle is to verify these foundations bottom-up before blaming the app, because a single failed foundation service can produce dozens of unrelated-looking application errors at once.</p><h3>DHCP failures</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>DHCP</span> assigns IP addresses, masks, gateways, and DNS servers. When it fails, hosts either get no address or fall back to an APIPA address in the 169.254.0.0/16 range - a dead giveaway. In a cloud VPC, DHCP is provided by the platform and configured through a DHCP option set; a wrong option set can hand instances the wrong DNS servers or domain name, which then cascades into resolution failures that look like DNS problems. The first check is whether the host received a sane lease:</p><pre><code>$ ip addr show eth0\n    inet 169.254.214.7/16 ... scope link eth0   # APIPA = no DHCP reply\n$ journalctl -u systemd-networkd | grep -i dhcp\n  eth0: DHCPv4 address request timed out</code></pre><p>A 169.254 address means no DHCP server answered - check that the option set is attached, the scope is not exhausted, and the subnet route to the DHCP service is intact. In the cloud, a custom DHCP option set that points at a broken on-prem DNS resolver is a common self-inflicted cause, and because the option set is applied at the VPC level, one bad edit can simultaneously break name resolution for every instance in the VPC - a wide blast radius that makes the change worth reviewing carefully.</p><h3>DNS failures</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>DNS</span> resolves names to addresses, and DNS problems masquerade as everything from slow page loads to total outages. The decisive test is to resolve the name directly and watch where it breaks:</p><pre><code>$ dig +short api.example-cloud.com\n$   # empty = name does not resolve\n$ dig api.example-cloud.com @8.8.8.8\n;; ANSWER SECTION:\napi.example-cloud.com.  60  IN  A  203.0.113.42\n$ nslookup api.example-cloud.com\n;; connection timed out; no servers could be reached\n$ cat /etc/resolv.conf\nnameserver 10.0.0.2   # is this the right VPC resolver?</code></pre><p>If <code>dig @8.8.8.8</code> succeeds but the default resolver fails, the record exists and the problem is your configured DNS server (a bad <code>resolv.conf</code> or VPC resolver). If even the public resolver returns nothing, the record itself is missing or the zone is broken. This split-resolver test instantly tells you whether the fault is in your network path or in the authoritative zone. A frequent cloud variation is split-horizon DNS, where an internal name resolves only from inside the VPC; querying a public resolver for such a name correctly returns nothing, and that is expected behavior rather than a fault.</p><h3>NTP failures</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>NTP</span> keeps clocks synchronized, and clock drift causes failures that look nothing like a time problem: TLS handshakes fail because certificate validity windows appear invalid, authentication tokens (SAML, Kerberos, signed API requests) are rejected for being outside their tolerance, and log timelines become impossible to correlate. AWS Signature requests reject a clock skewed more than a few minutes with <code>RequestTimeTooSkewed</code>. Confirm sync state directly:</p><pre><code>$ timedatectl\n               Local time: Sun 2026-06-28 14:02:11 UTC\n           Synchronized: no\n            NTP service: active\n$ chronyc tracking\nReference ID    : 00000000 ()\nLeap status     : Not synchronised</code></pre><p>An unsynchronized clock with active NTP usually means the host cannot reach its time source - often a security group or route blocking UDP 123. The fix is to open the path to the time source (the cloud provider's local NTP endpoint is the safest choice) rather than disabling certificate validation, which would trade a time bug for a security hole.</p><h3>NAT failures</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>NAT</span> lets private instances reach the internet without public IPs. When the NAT gateway is missing, in a failed AZ, or unreferenced by the route table, private instances lose all outbound connectivity - package installs hang, API calls to the provider time out, and updates fail. The symptom is that a private host can reach other private hosts but nothing on the internet:</p><pre><code>$ curl -s -m 5 https://api.example-cloud.com/ -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}\\n'\n000   # 000 + timeout from a private subnet = no outbound path (NAT/route)\n$ ping -c 2 10.0.2.10\n64 bytes from 10.0.2.10: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=0.5 ms   # private peer is fine\n$ ip route get 8.8.8.8\n8.8.8.8 via 10.0.0.1 dev eth0   # default route exists; is it a live NAT target?</code></pre><p>Private-to-private works but private-to-internet fails - that asymmetry is the NAT signature. Confirm the route table for the private subnet sends 0.0.0.0/0 to a healthy NAT gateway in the same AZ, because a NAT gateway in a failed AZ leaves the subnets that depend on it stranded.</p><h3>Why the order of services matters</h3><p>These four foundation services have a dependency order that shapes how you triage, and following that order keeps you from chasing phantom application bugs. DHCP must succeed first, because without an address and a configured resolver the host cannot do anything else; an APIPA address therefore makes every higher-layer symptom moot until it is fixed. DNS comes next, because almost every modern request begins with a name lookup, so a broken resolver manifests as failures across dozens of unrelated services at once. NTP is quieter but underpins all of cryptography and authentication, so a skewed clock silently breaks TLS and token validation even when DHCP and DNS are perfect. NAT sits at the edge of the path, governing whether private workloads can reach external dependencies at all. When several services are failing simultaneously, resist the urge to fix them in the order you noticed them; fix them in dependency order, because repairing DHCP or DNS frequently clears a cascade of downstream symptoms in one move. This is the bottom-up methodology from the opening section applied to the network stack: prove each foundation healthy before climbing to the next, and never debug an application timeout before you have confirmed that name resolution and outbound routing actually work.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Tie the symptom to the service: a 169.254 address means <strong>DHCP</strong>; names not resolving means <strong>DNS</strong> (use the split <code>dig @public</code> test to locate it); TLS/auth failures with valid certs point to <strong>NTP</strong> clock skew; private hosts that reach each other but not the internet means <strong>NAT</strong>/routing. Always verify these foundations before you touch the application.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[6].push(
  {heading:"Network Issues: HTTP Status Triage, Latency, and Throughput", body:"<p>Above the core services sits HTTP, where most cloud applications speak. Reading HTTP status codes correctly is a high-yield skill because the first digit tells you immediately which side of the connection owns the problem, and from there latency and throughput problems each have their own diagnostic signature. Mastering this triage means you can route a ticket to the right team - client, application, or platform - in seconds rather than minutes.</p><h3>HTTP status code triage</h3><p>The decisive split is the leading digit: a <code>4xx</code> means the <em>client</em> sent a bad request (your call is wrong), while a <code>5xx</code> means the <em>server or an intermediary</em> failed (the backend is broken). A verbose request shows the code, the headers, and timing in one shot:</p><pre><code>$ curl -v https://app.example-cloud.com/api/orders\n&lt; HTTP/2 502\n&lt; via: 1.1 cloudfront\n&lt; x-cache: Error from cloudfront</code></pre><table><thead><tr><th>Status</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Likely cloud cause</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>400</td><td>Bad Request</td><td>Malformed payload or query from the client</td></tr><tr><td>401 / 403</td><td>Unauthorized / Forbidden</td><td>Missing/expired token; IAM or WAF denial</td></tr><tr><td>404</td><td>Not Found</td><td>Wrong path, deleted object, bad routing rule</td></tr><tr><td>429</td><td>Too Many Requests</td><td>Rate limiting / API throttling - back off</td></tr><tr><td>500</td><td>Internal Server Error</td><td>Unhandled exception in the application code</td></tr><tr><td>502</td><td>Bad Gateway</td><td>LB/proxy got an invalid reply from an unhealthy backend</td></tr><tr><td>503</td><td>Service Unavailable</td><td>No healthy targets, or service overloaded</td></tr><tr><td>504</td><td>Gateway Timeout</td><td>Backend too slow; upstream timed out</td></tr></tbody></table><p>The 502/503/504 family is the load balancer telling you about the backend. A <strong>503</strong> from an ALB usually means the target group has zero healthy targets; a <strong>504</strong> means a target accepted the connection but did not answer within the idle timeout - a slow query or a hung dependency. Confirm by checking target health:</p><pre><code>$ aws elbv2 describe-target-health --target-group-arn arn:...:targetgroup/web/abc \\\n    --query 'TargetHealthDescriptions[].TargetHealth.[State,Reason]' --output text\nunhealthy   Target.FailedHealthChecks</code></pre><p>If every target is unhealthy, the load balancer has nowhere to send traffic and must return 503; the next move is to find out why the health check is failing - wrong path, wrong port, or a genuinely crashed application.</p><h3>Latency</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Latency</span> is delay - the time for a packet or request to make the round trip. High latency degrades user experience without producing errors, so it hides from naive health checks. <code>ping</code> measures network round-trip time, while <code>curl</code> timing breakdowns reveal where the delay accumulates:</p><pre><code>$ ping -c 4 db.internal\n64 bytes from 10.0.2.9: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=0.6 ms\n$ curl -s -o /dev/null -w 'dns=%{time_namelookup} connect=%{time_connect} ttfb=%{time_starttransfer} total=%{time_total}\\n' https://app.example-cloud.com/\ndns=0.004 connect=0.031 ttfb=1.812 total=1.840</code></pre><p>Here connect is fast but time-to-first-byte is 1.8s - the network is fine and the application or database is slow. If instead <code>time_namelookup</code> were large, DNS would be the culprit; if <code>time_connect</code> dominated, the network path or TLS handshake would be. Splitting the timeline by phase is the fastest way to attribute latency to the right layer, and it is far more precise than a single round-trip number from ping.</p><h3>Bandwidth and throughput</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Bandwidth</span> is the maximum capacity of a link; <span class='keyterm'>throughput</span> is the rate actually achieved. A throughput problem looks like slow bulk transfers, stalled replication, or backups that miss their window, even when latency is low. Causes include instance-class network caps, undersized links, or congestion. Measure achieved throughput directly with <code>iperf3</code>, and watch for interface saturation or errors:</p><pre><code>$ iperf3 -c 10.0.3.20\n[  5]   0.00-10.00  sec  1.05 GBytes   902 Mbits/sec   receiver\n$ ip -s link show eth0\n    RX: bytes  packets  errors  dropped\n    ...                    0       1423   # dropped packets = congestion/cap</code></pre><p>If achieved throughput sits near a round number (say 5 Gbps) regardless of load, you have likely hit the instance's network performance ceiling - the fix is a larger instance class or enhanced networking, not application tuning.</p><h3>Latency versus throughput - they are not the same</h3><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Latency</th><th>Throughput</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Measures</td><td>Delay per round trip</td><td>Data moved per second</td></tr><tr><td>Tool</td><td>ping, curl TTFB</td><td>iperf3, transfer timing</td></tr><tr><td>Symptom</td><td>Sluggish interactive requests</td><td>Slow bulk transfers/backups</td></tr><tr><td>Common fix</td><td>Move closer (region/CDN), tune query</td><td>Bigger instance class, enhanced networking</td></tr></tbody></table><p>A link can have high bandwidth but terrible latency (a satellite path) or low latency but limited throughput (a small instance close by). Diagnosing the wrong one wastes effort, so always confirm which metric the user is actually complaining about before reaching for a fix.</p><h3>Packet loss and the metric that hides behind latency</h3><p>A third dimension often masquerades as both latency and throughput: <span class='keyterm'>packet loss</span>. Even a small loss rate forces TCP to retransmit and back off its congestion window, which inflates effective latency and collapses throughput far out of proportion to the raw loss percentage. The clue is in the ping summary and the interface error counters rather than in a single round-trip number:</p><pre><code>$ ping -c 100 -q db.internal | tail -2\n100 packets transmitted, 94 received, 6% packet loss\nrtt min/avg/max/mdev = 0.5/4.2/180.0/22.1 ms   # huge max + mdev = loss/jitter\n$ netstat -s | grep -i retrans\n    1843 segments retransmitted   # TCP is fighting loss on this path</code></pre><p>A high maximum and standard deviation alongside a low average is the fingerprint of intermittent loss and jitter, not steady latency. The remediation differs again: loss usually points to a saturated link, a flapping interface, or an overloaded middlebox, so you look for the congested hop with <code>mtr</code> or repeated <code>traceroute</code> runs rather than resizing the application. Distinguishing latency, throughput, and loss is the difference between fixing the real bottleneck and tuning a parameter that was never the problem.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>First digit decides ownership: <strong>4xx = client error</strong> (fix the request, the token, or the path), <strong>5xx = server/gateway error</strong> (fix the backend, scaling, or timeout). A 503 from a load balancer almost always means no healthy targets. Distinguish <strong>latency</strong> (delay, measured by ping/TTFB) from <strong>throughput</strong> (rate, measured by iperf3) - they have different fixes.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[6].push(
  {heading:"Network Issues: Device Misconfiguration and Protocol Problems", body:"<p>This section covers two related causes: network device misconfiguration - in the cloud, that means security groups, network ACLs, load balancers, and gateways - and protocol incompatibility or deprecation. Both produce connection failures that look identical from the application, so the diagnostic art is locating exactly where packets stop. The single most useful distinction in the entire objective is timeout versus refused, because it splits the problem space cleanly in half before you touch a single configuration screen.</p><h3>Network device misconfiguration in the cloud</h3><p>On-premises this meant a mistyped switch or firewall rule; in the cloud the equivalent devices are <span class='keyterm'>security groups</span> (stateful, instance-level), <span class='keyterm'>network ACLs</span> (stateless, subnet-level), and managed gateways. The classic failure is a connection that times out because a rule does not permit the port. The key clue is <em>timeout versus refused</em>: a connection that hangs and times out usually means a firewall is silently dropping the packet, while an immediate <code>Connection refused</code> means the packet arrived but nothing is listening. Test the specific port end to end:</p><pre><code>$ nc -zv db.internal 5432\nnc: connect to db.internal port 5432 (tcp) timed out   # dropped -> security group/NACL\n$ nc -zv app.internal 8080\nnc: connect to app.internal port 8080 (tcp) failed: Connection refused   # reached host, no listener\n$ ss -tlnp | grep 8080\n$   # nothing listening on 8080 confirms the refusal is a service problem</code></pre><p>A timeout sends you to the firewall rules; a refusal sends you to the service (is it running and bound to the right interface?). Because a NACL is <em>stateless</em>, a common gotcha is allowing inbound traffic but forgetting the outbound rule for the ephemeral return ports - the request arrives but the reply is dropped, producing a one-way hang that a stateful security group would never cause. A third outcome worth recognizing is a connection that establishes and then resets unexpectedly, which usually means the service is reachable but actively closing the connection - an application-level rejection, a TLS mismatch, or an idle-timeout closure rather than a firewall drop. Distinguishing drop, refuse, and reset is the foundation of network-device triage because each points at a different layer and a different team.</p><h3>Security group versus network ACL</h3><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Security group</th><th>Network ACL</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Scope</td><td>Instance / ENI</td><td>Subnet</td></tr><tr><td>State</td><td>Stateful (return traffic auto-allowed)</td><td>Stateless (must allow return explicitly)</td></tr><tr><td>Rules</td><td>Allow only</td><td>Allow and deny, evaluated in order</td></tr><tr><td>Common bug</td><td>Missing inbound allow for the port</td><td>Forgotten outbound ephemeral-port allow</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Load balancer and gateway misconfiguration</h3><p>Managed devices fail in characteristic ways: a listener on the wrong port, a target group with a health-check path that returns 404 so every target is marked unhealthy, or a missing internet gateway so a public subnet has no route out. The 503 from the previous section is frequently a health-check misconfiguration rather than a truly broken backend - the app is fine but the probe checks <code>/</code> when the app only answers on <code>/healthz</code>. Verifying the health-check path against the application directly is a two-second test that saves a long hunt:</p><pre><code>$ curl -s -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}\\n' http://10.0.2.15:8080/\n404   # LB health check hits / and sees 404 -> marks target unhealthy\n$ curl -s -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}\\n' http://10.0.2.15:8080/healthz\n200   # app is actually fine; fix the health-check path on the target group</code></pre><h3>Protocol incompatibility and deprecation</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Protocol incompatibility</span> arises when two endpoints cannot agree on how to talk: a client offering only HTTP/1.1 to a server that requires HTTP/2, an SMB version mismatch, or a database driver speaking an old wire protocol. <span class='keyterm'>Protocol deprecation</span> is the planned removal of an old protocol for security reasons - the most heavily tested example is TLS. When a provider disables TLS 1.0/1.1, a legacy client that cannot negotiate TLS 1.2+ fails the handshake even though DNS, routing, and credentials are all correct. Diagnose the handshake explicitly:</p><pre><code>$ curl -v --tlsv1.0 https://api.example-cloud.com/ 2&gt;&amp;1 | grep -i 'alert\\|protocol'\n* OpenSSL: error:0A000410:SSL routines::sslv3 alert handshake failure\n$ openssl s_client -connect api.example-cloud.com:443 -tls1_2 &lt;/dev/null 2&gt;/dev/null | grep -i 'protocol\\|cipher'\n    Protocol  : TLSv1.2\n    Cipher    : ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256</code></pre><p>If forcing TLS 1.0 produces a handshake-failure alert but TLS 1.2 succeeds, the server has deprecated old TLS and the fix is to upgrade the client or its TLS library - not to weaken the server back down, which would reintroduce the vulnerability the deprecation was meant to close.</p><h3>Asymmetric and intermittent device faults</h3><p>The hardest device misconfigurations to diagnose are the asymmetric and intermittent ones. An asymmetric fault lets traffic flow in one direction but not the return, which the stateless-NACL example already illustrates; another common cause is a misconfigured load-balancer security group that permits inbound client traffic but lacks the egress rule to reach the backend targets, so the front half of the path looks healthy while the back half silently drops. Intermittent faults appear when only some members of a pool are misconfigured - for instance three of five targets sit in a subnet whose route to the database was never added, so roughly forty percent of requests fail at random while a quick test against a healthy target succeeds and convinces you nothing is wrong. The discipline for both is to test every leg of the path explicitly rather than trusting a single sample: probe client-to-LB, LB-to-each-target, and target-to-dependency as separate hops. When a failure rate is a clean fraction like one-in-three or two-in-five, suspect a partially misconfigured pool rather than a global outage, because a uniform problem would fail every request, not a consistent slice of them.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Layer</th><th>Likely cause</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Connection times out</td><td>Network filtering</td><td>Security group / NACL drops the port</td></tr><tr><td>Connection refused</td><td>Host / service</td><td>Service down or bound to wrong interface</td></tr><tr><td>One-way hang</td><td>Stateless NACL</td><td>Return traffic on ephemeral ports blocked</td></tr><tr><td>TLS handshake failure</td><td>Protocol</td><td>Deprecated TLS version or no shared cipher</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><strong>Timeout</strong> implicates a firewall/security group silently dropping packets; <strong>Connection refused</strong> implicates the host/service. Remember NACLs are <em>stateless</em> - you must allow return traffic explicitly. A TLS handshake failure after a provider hardening change points to <strong>protocol deprecation</strong>: upgrade the client, never downgrade the server.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[6].push(
  {heading:"Network Issues: IP Addressing, Routing, and Switching", body:"<p>The deepest network layer in objective 6.2 covers Layer 3 addressing and routing plus Layer 2 switching. In the cloud these become VPC CIDR design, route tables, and VLAN/subnet tagging - and mistakes here cause failures that no application change can fix. These problems are particularly frustrating because the application logs look clean: the packets never reach the application at all, or never find their way back. The instinct to add retries, raise timeouts, or restart the service produces no improvement, because the fault lives below the application entirely; recognizing that early is what stops a Layer 3 problem from being misdiagnosed as a flaky app for hours. The reliable tell is that connectivity failures here are deterministic with respect to destination - a given address or subnet is always unreachable, or always reachable, rather than intermittently slow - which points the investigation at addressing and forwarding rather than at code.</p><h3>IP addressing issues</h3><p>Two named problems dominate. <span class='keyterm'>Scope exhaustion</span> is running out of addresses: a subnet sized as a /27 has only ~27 usable IPs after the cloud reserves several, so an autoscaling group that tries to launch the 28th instance fails with <code>InsufficientFreeAddressesInSubnet</code>. <span class='keyterm'>Network overlap</span> is when two networks that must connect use the same CIDR range - the classic VPC-peering or VPN failure where both sides use 10.0.0.0/16, so routing becomes ambiguous and traffic to the overlapping range never crosses. Diagnose exhaustion by counting free addresses; diagnose overlap by comparing CIDRs:</p><pre><code>$ aws ec2 describe-subnets --subnet-ids subnet-0ab1 \\\n    --query 'Subnets[0].[CidrBlock,AvailableIpAddressCount]' --output text\n10.0.5.0/27   0      # zero free addresses = scope exhaustion\n$ # peering: VPC-A 10.0.0.0/16 and VPC-B 10.0.0.0/16 overlap -> peering rejected</code></pre><p>Scope exhaustion is fixed by a larger subnet or a secondary CIDR; overlap is fixed only by re-addressing one side or using NAT to translate between them - you cannot route between two identical ranges, because the router has no way to know which side an address belongs to. This is why CIDR planning at the very start of a cloud footprint matters so much: a poorly chosen address plan becomes nearly impossible to peer with partners and acquisitions later. A useful preventive habit is to carve the organization's address space into non-overlapping blocks per environment and per region before the first VPC is built, leaving deliberate headroom so that subnets can grow without bumping into a neighbor. Exhaustion also hides in plain sight when container networking assigns an address per pod rather than per node: a cluster that schedules thousands of pods can drain a subnet far faster than the node count alone would suggest, so sizing the subnet for the pod density, not just the instance count, is part of the design.</p><h3>Routing issues</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Missing routes</span> and <span class='keyterm'>misconfigured routes</span> are the two routing faults. A missing route means there is no path entry for the destination, so traffic dies at the gateway; a misconfigured route sends traffic to the wrong target - for example a default route pointing at a deleted NAT gateway, or a more-specific route shadowing the one you intended (longest-prefix match wins). Trace the actual path and inspect the table:</p><pre><code>$ traceroute -n 203.0.113.42\n 1  10.0.5.1   0.4 ms          # local gateway\n 2  * * *                       # path dies here -> missing/black-hole route\n$ ip route\ndefault via 10.0.5.1 dev eth0\n10.0.0.0/16 dev eth0 scope link\n$ ip route get 203.0.113.42\n203.0.113.42 via 10.0.5.1 dev eth0   # which next hop is actually chosen</code></pre><p>A traceroute that reaches the first hop and then shows nothing but timeouts points to a missing or black-holed route beyond your gateway. In the cloud, confirm the VPC route table actually has an entry for the destination CIDR pointing at a live target (internet gateway, NAT, peering connection, or transit gateway). A classic misconfiguration is a route that still points at a NAT gateway or peering connection that has since been deleted - the entry exists but its target is dead, so traffic is silently dropped. Equally common is the asymmetry trap, where the outbound route exists but the return route on the far side was never added, so the request arrives but the reply has no path home; this is why routing must always be verified in both directions, since a one-way route table looks perfectly correct from the side you happen to inspect first.</p><h3>Switching and VLAN issues</h3><p>At Layer 2, the exam focuses on <span class='keyterm'>VLAN issues</span> - misconfigured tags and the access-versus-trunk port distinction. An <span class='keyterm'>access port</span> carries a single untagged VLAN to an end device; a <span class='keyterm'>trunk port</span> carries multiple tagged VLANs between switches. The classic faults are putting a device on the wrong VLAN (it gets an address in the wrong subnet and cannot reach its intended peers), a trunk that does not allow the VLAN it needs to carry, or a native-VLAN mismatch between two trunk ends that causes one VLAN's traffic to leak into another.</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Access port</th><th>Trunk port</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>VLANs carried</td><td>One</td><td>Many</td></tr><tr><td>Tagging</td><td>Untagged to the device</td><td>802.1Q tagged frames</td></tr><tr><td>Connects</td><td>End host (server, phone)</td><td>Switch-to-switch / hypervisor uplink</td></tr><tr><td>Common fault</td><td>Wrong VLAN = wrong subnet</td><td>VLAN not allowed / native mismatch</td></tr></tbody></table><p>The tell for a misconfigured tag is a host that gets a link but lands in the wrong subnet or cannot see its expected neighbors despite a healthy physical connection. In virtualized and cloud-adjacent environments, the same logic applies to hypervisor port groups and overlay segments - a VM attached to the wrong port group is the modern equivalent of a misconfigured access port. You can spot the symptom from the host: a link-up interface that received an address in an unexpected subnet, or one that cannot ARP for its own gateway.</p><pre><code>$ ip addr show eth0 | grep inet\n    inet 192.168.50.23/24   # expected 10.0.5.x -> wrong VLAN/port group\n$ arping -c 2 10.0.5.1\nTimeout   # cannot reach the gateway it should be on -> Layer 2 tagging fault</code></pre><h3>Layer 3 versus Layer 2 - deciding which to investigate</h3><p>Because addressing/routing (Layer 3) and switching/VLAN (Layer 2) faults can both leave a host unable to reach its destination, the diagnostic question is which layer to examine first. The fastest discriminator is whether the host even has a correct address on the correct subnet. If the interface shows an address in the wrong range, or cannot ARP for its own default gateway, the problem is below Layer 3 - a VLAN tag, port-group, or DHCP-scope fault - and no amount of route-table editing will help. If the address and the local gateway are correct but a remote destination is unreachable, the problem is at Layer 3: a missing route, a dead next hop, or an overlapping CIDR. Put plainly, an inability to reach your own gateway is a Layer 2 symptom, while an inability to reach a destination beyond a healthy gateway is a Layer 3 symptom. This single test saves enormous time, because it tells you whether to open the switch/port-group configuration or the route table, and stops you from rewriting routes when the real fault is that the host was never on the right segment to begin with. In cloud terms, the equivalent of the wrong VLAN is the wrong subnet association or the wrong ENI, and the equivalent of a missing route is an absent or black-holed route-table entry - the same two-layer logic, expressed in VPC primitives.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A new VPC peering connection is created but traffic never flows. IAM is fine and the route tables have entries. The cause is <strong>network overlap</strong>: both VPCs use 10.0.0.0/16, so the peering refuses overlapping CIDRs. The only fix is to re-address one VPC - no route or firewall change can route between identical ranges.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><strong>Scope exhaustion</strong> = no free IPs (resize the subnet); <strong>overlap</strong> = identical CIDRs that cannot be peered (re-address one side). A traceroute that dies after the first hop suggests a <strong>missing route</strong>. For switching, remember access = one untagged VLAN to a host, trunk = many tagged VLANs between switches; a host in the wrong subnet on a good link is usually a <strong>VLAN tag</strong> error.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[6].push(
  {heading:"Security Issues: Cipher Deprecation, Encryption, and Vulnerabilities", body:"<p>Objective 6.3 turns to security symptoms. The first cluster involves cryptography and code weaknesses: deprecated cipher suites, missing protocol encryption, and software vulnerabilities. These produce failures that range from a broken handshake to a silent data exposure, and the troubleshooter must recognize the security root cause rather than papering over it. The recurring exam theme in this section is that the wrong fix - weakening a control to make a symptom go away - is always one of the offered answers, and is always wrong.</p><h3>Cipher suite deprecation</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>cipher suite</span> is the negotiated bundle of algorithms (key exchange, authentication, bulk encryption, and MAC) that secures a TLS session. Over time, suites are <span class='keyterm'>deprecated</span> as cryptographers find weaknesses - RC4, 3DES, CBC-mode suites vulnerable to padding attacks, and anything using SHA-1 or export-grade keys. When a provider or load balancer security policy drops a weak suite, a legacy client that offers <em>only</em> that suite can no longer connect, producing a handshake failure that looks like an outage. The diagnosis is to enumerate what each side supports:</p><pre><code>$ nmap --script ssl-enum-ciphers -p 443 api.example-cloud.com | grep -A2 TLSv1.2\n|   TLSv1.2:\n|     ciphers:\n|       TLS_ECDHE_RSA_WITH_AES_128_GCM_SHA256 (secp256r1) - A\n$ openssl s_client -connect api.example-cloud.com:443 -cipher RC4-SHA &lt;/dev/null\n139... no cipher match   # server refuses the deprecated cipher</code></pre><p>If the server only offers modern suites and the client demands a deprecated one, the fix is to update the client's TLS library, never to re-enable the weak cipher on the server. Re-enabling RC4 to make an old client work trades a connectivity ticket for a real vulnerability - exactly the wrong call the exam wants you to reject. The nmap grade column (A, B, C, F) is a quick way to confirm the server's policy is actually hardened. The same logic governs TLS protocol versions and signature algorithms: when a hardening change breaks a single legacy integration, the correct path is to isolate or upgrade that integration, not to roll the whole endpoint back to an insecure baseline for everyone. Compliance regimes such as PCI DSS mandate the removal of weak ciphers and old TLS versions outright, so re-enabling them can fail an audit even if it temporarily restores connectivity for one stubborn client.</p><h3>Lack of encryption in protocols</h3><p>A distinct issue is a protocol carrying data with <span class='keyterm'>no encryption at all</span>: plain HTTP, FTP, Telnet, unauthenticated SMTP, or a database connection without TLS. The symptom may not be a failure - the application works fine - which is what makes it dangerous. A packet capture proves whether credentials and data are traveling in cleartext:</p><pre><code>$ sudo tcpdump -i eth0 -A -n 'tcp port 80 and host app.internal'\n... POST /login HTTP/1.1\n... username=admin&amp;password=Sup3rSecret!    # cleartext credentials = no encryption</code></pre><p>Seeing the password in the capture is the proof. The remediation is to enforce encryption in transit - redirect HTTP to HTTPS, replace FTP with SFTP/FTPS, require TLS on database connections, and ideally use a security-group or policy control that blocks the cleartext port entirely so it cannot be used by accident.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Insecure protocol</th><th>Port</th><th>Encrypted replacement</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>HTTP</td><td>80</td><td>HTTPS (443)</td></tr><tr><td>FTP</td><td>21</td><td>SFTP (22) / FTPS</td></tr><tr><td>Telnet</td><td>23</td><td>SSH (22)</td></tr><tr><td>SMTP (cleartext)</td><td>25</td><td>SMTP+STARTTLS / SMTPS (465)</td></tr><tr><td>LDAP</td><td>389</td><td>LDAPS (636)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Software vulnerability issues</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>software vulnerability</span> is a flaw in code or a dependency that an attacker can exploit - an unpatched CVE in a library, a base image with a known issue, or an outdated runtime. In cloud workflows these are found by scanning images and dependencies, ideally in the pipeline before deploy so a vulnerable artifact never reaches production:</p><pre><code>$ trivy image myapp:1.4.0\nmyapp:1.4.0 (debian 12)\nTotal: 3 (CRITICAL: 1)\n+-------------+-----------------+----------+-------------------+\n| LIBRARY     | VULNERABILITY   | SEVERITY | FIXED VERSION     |\n+-------------+-----------------+----------+-------------------+\n| libssl3     | CVE-2026-1234   | CRITICAL | 3.0.14-1          |\n+-------------+-----------------+----------+-------------------+</code></pre><p>The output names the vulnerable library, the CVE, the severity, and the fixed version - turning an abstract risk into a concrete patch action. The fix is to rebuild on a patched base image or bump the dependency, then redeploy; suppressing the finding without patching is the trap. A mature pipeline fails the build when a CRITICAL with a known fix is present, so the vulnerability is caught before it ever ships.</p><h3>Choosing the right remediation</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Issue</th><th>Tell</th><th>Right fix</th><th>Wrong fix to reject</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cipher deprecation</td><td>Handshake fails only for old clients</td><td>Upgrade client; keep server hardened</td><td>Re-enable RC4/3DES</td></tr><tr><td>No encryption in protocol</td><td>Cleartext data visible in capture</td><td>Enforce TLS/SFTP; block cleartext port</td><td>Leave it because it works</td></tr><tr><td>Software vulnerability</td><td>Scanner reports a fixable CVE</td><td>Patch/rebuild and redeploy</td><td>Suppress the alert</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>When a security control change breaks an old client, the answer is almost never to weaken the control. Upgrade the client to support modern ciphers/TLS; do not re-enable a deprecated cipher suite. A protocol that <em>works</em> but exposes cleartext is still a finding - encrypt it. And a scanned CVE is fixed by patching, not by suppressing the alert.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[6].push(
  {heading:"Security Issues: Authentication and Authorization Failures", body:"<p>Identity is the cloud's primary control surface, so authentication and authorization failures are both the most common security tickets and the most dangerous incidents. The troubleshooter must tell a benign misconfiguration apart from an active compromise - and the exam tests that distinction directly. The mental model to carry in is that authentication answers who you are while authorization answers what you may do, and the diagnostic tools, the symptoms, and the correct first response all differ between the two.</p><h3>Authentication issues and leaked credentials</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Authentication</span> answers who you are. Benign authentication failures are everyday - an expired password, a clock-skew rejected token (the NTP link from earlier), a missing MFA enrollment. But the failure the exam emphasizes is <span class='keyterm'>leaked credentials</span>: an access key committed to a public Git repository, a password reused and exposed in a breach, or a token captured by phishing. The signature of leaked credentials is not a failure to log in - it is a <em>successful</em> login from an impossible or unexpected context. Audit logs are the diagnostic tool:</p><pre><code>$ aws cloudtrail lookup-events \\\n    --lookup-attributes AttributeKey=AccessKeyId,AttributeValue=AKIAEXAMPLE \\\n    --query 'Events[].[EventTime,Username,EventName,SourceIPAddress]' --output text\n2026-06-28T03:14Z  ci-deploy  RunInstances    198.51.100.7    # unfamiliar IP, odd hour\n2026-06-28T03:15Z  ci-deploy  CreateUser      198.51.100.7</code></pre><p>A service account that normally only deploys suddenly creating IAM users from an unfamiliar IP is a textbook leaked-credential indicator. The response is immediate: revoke and rotate the credential, then investigate what it touched. The exam wants the <em>order</em> - contain the leaked key first, then perform forensics; never leave an exposed key active while you investigate. Disabling the key is reversible and stops the bleeding; the forensic timeline can be reconstructed from logs afterward.</p><pre><code>$ aws iam update-access-key --access-key-id AKIAEXAMPLE \\\n    --status Inactive --user-name ci-deploy   # contain first\n$ aws iam list-access-keys --user-name ci-deploy   # then enumerate and rotate</code></pre><h3>Authorization issues</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Authorization</span> answers what you may do. Two named failures sit here. <span class='keyterm'>Unauthorized access</span> is a subject reaching a resource it should not - often the result of an over-broad policy (a wildcard <code>Action: *</code> or <code>Resource: *</code>), a public bucket, or a missing condition. <span class='keyterm'>Privilege escalation</span> is a subject gaining <em>more</em> rights than granted, typically by abusing a permission like <code>iam:PassRole</code>, attaching an admin policy to itself, or exploiting a misconfigured role-assumption chain. Authorization problems show up as a 403 when too tight and as a quiet, successful-but-improper action when too loose. Simulate a policy to test what an identity can actually do:</p><pre><code>$ aws iam simulate-principal-policy \\\n    --policy-source-arn arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/app-role \\\n    --action-names s3:DeleteBucket iam:AttachUserPolicy \\\n    --query 'EvaluationResults[].[EvalActionName,EvalDecision]' --output text\ns3:DeleteBucket       allowed   # app-role should NOT be able to delete buckets\niam:AttachUserPolicy  allowed   # and definitely should not attach policies</code></pre><p>An <code>allowed</code> result for an action the role should never perform reveals an over-permissioned policy - the latent path to both unauthorized access and privilege escalation. The remediation is least privilege: scope actions and resources tightly, remove wildcards, and add conditions. A role that can call <code>iam:AttachUserPolicy</code> or <code>iam:PassRole</code> on a powerful role is effectively an admin role in disguise, which is exactly the escalation path attackers hunt for.</p><h3>The deny-by-default evaluation logic</h3><p>To troubleshoot authorization confidently you have to understand how the policy engine actually decides, because the answer is rarely as simple as one allow statement. In most cloud IAM models the evaluation is deny-by-default with an explicit-deny override: a request is denied unless some policy explicitly allows it, and a single explicit deny anywhere - in an identity policy, a resource policy, a permission boundary, or an organization service-control policy - overrides every allow. This is why a 403 can be baffling: the engineer sees an allow statement attached to the role and assumes access should work, not realizing that a permission boundary or an SCP one level up is vetoing it. The correct diagnostic move is to evaluate the <em>effective</em> permissions across all layers rather than reading a single policy document, which is exactly what the policy simulator and access-analyzer tools do. When a needed action is denied despite an apparent allow, walk the layers from most specific to most general looking for the explicit deny; when an action succeeds that should not, look for the over-broad allow with no countervailing deny. Holding this model in mind turns authorization troubleshooting from guesswork into a deterministic search through a small, well-defined set of policy sources.</p><h3>Authentication versus authorization at a glance</h3><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Authentication issue</th><th>Authorization issue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Question answered</td><td>Who are you?</td><td>What may you do?</td></tr><tr><td>Benign symptom</td><td>Login fails (expired pw, clock skew)</td><td>403 Forbidden on a needed action</td></tr><tr><td>Malicious symptom</td><td>Successful login from a strange context (leaked creds)</td><td>Action succeeds that should be denied (priv-esc / unauthorized access)</td></tr><tr><td>Diagnostic tool</td><td>Auth logs, CloudTrail sign-in events</td><td>Policy simulator, access analyzer</td></tr><tr><td>First response</td><td>Revoke and rotate the credential</td><td>Tighten the policy to least privilege</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>CloudTrail shows a deploy key that normally runs <code>RunInstances</code> from the CI provider's IP suddenly calling <code>CreateAccessKey</code> and <code>AttachUserPolicy</code> from a residential IP at 3 a.m. This is leaked credentials being used for privilege escalation. The correct sequence is contain first - disable the key immediately - then investigate scope and remediate the over-broad permissions that allowed the escalation.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Authentication is identity; authorization is permission. <strong>Leaked credentials</strong> reveal themselves as <em>successful</em> logins from unexpected contexts - the fix is revoke-and-rotate, before forensics. <strong>Privilege escalation</strong> and <strong>unauthorized access</strong> are authorization failures fixed by least privilege. When a question lists steps, contain the compromised credential before you investigate.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[6].push(
  {heading:"Security Issues: Unauthorized Software and Data Security", body:"<p>The last objectives in Domain 6 cover threats that arrive as rogue software or as exposed data. Both are detection-and-response problems as much as configuration problems, and both lean on the cloud's audit and inventory capabilities to find the issue before it becomes a breach. The exam favors the preventive posture in both cases: the best answer is usually the guardrail that stops the problem at deploy time, not the heroic hunt that finds it after the fact.</p><h3>Unauthorized software</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Unauthorized software</span> is anything running in the environment that was not approved: shadow-IT agents, a developer's personal tool baked into an image, cryptomining malware dropped by an attacker, or a container pulled from an untrusted public registry. The danger is twofold - it may be malicious, and even if benign it widens the attack surface and breaks compliance baselines. Detection compares what is running against an approved inventory or baseline. On a host, unexpected processes and outbound connections are the tell:</p><pre><code>$ ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head -3\nUSER   PID  %CPU  COMMAND\nroot  4821  99.4  /tmp/.x/kdevtmpfsi              # high CPU, hidden path = likely miner\n$ ss -tunp | grep ESTAB\ntcp ESTAB 0 0 10.0.2.9:51344 45.83.12.7:3333  pid=4821 kdevtmpfsi   # mining pool port</code></pre><p>A process pegging the CPU from a hidden <code>/tmp</code> path and connecting outbound to a mining-pool port (3333) is a classic unauthorized-miner signature. In a managed cloud, the better control is preventive: enforce allow-listed registries, sign and verify images, and use a configuration/inventory service to flag any drift from the approved software baseline so unauthorized software is caught at deploy rather than discovered burning budget. A sudden, unexplained spike in compute cost is itself a detection signal worth investigating, because cryptomining shows up on the bill before anyone notices the process.</p><h3>Data security issues</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Data security issues</span> are exposures or mishandling of data itself - the canonical cloud incident is a storage bucket or database left publicly readable. Unlike a crashed service, a data exposure often produces no error and no performance symptom; the data simply leaks. Detection means auditing access policies and public-exposure settings directly rather than waiting for an alert:</p><pre><code>$ aws s3api get-public-access-block --bucket customer-records\n{\n  PublicAccessBlockConfiguration:\n    BlockPublicAcls: false\n    IgnorePublicAcls: false\n    BlockPublicPolicy: false\n    RestrictPublicBuckets: false\n}\n$ curl -s -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}\\n' https://customer-records.s3.amazonaws.com/\n200   # publicly reachable bucket listing = data exposure</code></pre><p>Every value being <code>false</code> means nothing blocks public access, and an anonymous <code>curl</code> returning <code>200</code> confirms the data is reachable from the internet. The fix is to enable the public-access block, scope the bucket policy to least privilege, and verify encryption at rest is on. Beyond confidentiality, data security also covers integrity and retention - ensuring data is not tampered with, that backups exist and are tested, and that classified data is encrypted and access-logged so any unusual read pattern is visible.</p><h3>Confirming encryption and access posture</h3><p>Encryption at rest is the safety net for a misconfigured access policy: even if an object is reachable, strong encryption with controlled keys limits what an attacker can do with it. Verify it explicitly rather than assuming the default applied:</p><pre><code>$ aws s3api get-bucket-encryption --bucket customer-records \\\n    --query 'ServerSideEncryptionConfiguration.Rules[0].ApplyServerSideEncryptionByDefault.SSEAlgorithm' --output text\nAES256   # encrypted at rest; confirm the KMS key policy is also least-privilege</code></pre><h3>Data in transit, in use, and the shared-responsibility line</h3><p>Data security spans three states, and a complete diagnosis checks all of them rather than fixating on storage. Data <em>at rest</em> is the bucket-or-volume encryption verified above. Data <em>in transit</em> is the TLS-everywhere posture from the protocols section: a perfectly locked-down bucket still leaks if the application fetches from it over plain HTTP across a shared network. Data <em>in use</em> - decrypted in memory while being processed - is the hardest to protect and increasingly addressed with confidential-computing enclaves, but for the exam the key point is simply recognizing that encryption at rest does not cover the moment the data is actually read and processed. Layering all three is what closes the gap an attacker would otherwise walk through. Underlying every data-security incident is the <span class='keyterm'>shared-responsibility model</span>: the provider secures the infrastructure and offers the controls (encryption options, public-access blocks, IAM), but the customer is responsible for turning those controls on and configuring them correctly. Nearly every headline cloud data breach has been a customer-side misconfiguration - a public bucket, an over-broad policy, an unencrypted snapshot shared too widely - rather than a failure of the provider's platform. Troubleshooting therefore starts from the assumption that the exposure is on your side of the line, and the fix is to apply the control the provider already made available.</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Unauthorized software</th><th>Data security issue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>What is wrong</td><td>Rogue/unapproved code is running</td><td>Data is exposed or mishandled</td></tr><tr><td>Tell</td><td>Unknown process, odd outbound conn, cost spike, baseline drift</td><td>Public bucket, no encryption, anomalous access</td></tr><tr><td>Detection</td><td>Inventory/baseline compare, process audit</td><td>Access-policy and public-exposure audit</td></tr><tr><td>Prevention</td><td>Allow-listed registries, image signing</td><td>Block public access, least-privilege policy, encryption</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>NOTE</div><p>Both issues are best solved before they occur. A configuration-management and inventory service that continuously compares running state to an approved baseline turns the reactive hunt for unauthorized software and exposed data into an automated alert - which is exactly the preventive posture the exam favors over after-the-fact discovery. Block-public-access at the account level, for example, makes the public-bucket mistake impossible rather than merely detectable.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><strong>Unauthorized software</strong> is found by comparing running state to an approved baseline/inventory - watch for hidden-path high-CPU processes, odd outbound connections (mining), and unexpected cost spikes. <strong>Data security</strong> incidents (a public bucket) often produce no error at all, so they are found by auditing access policies and public-exposure settings, then remediated with least-privilege and encryption. Prevention beats detection: allow-list registries and block public access by default.</p></div>"}
);
